Though it appears that the speculation in examples is informed, it is clear from figures \ref{fig:ES1} and \ref{fig:ES2} that exchange rates do not react instantly to the news.  There is a gradual evolution.  This is consistent with the evidence of serial correlation in asset prices that has been identified.  See, for example, \citet{Jagadeesh}.  It appears that information is gradually absorbed into the price.\footnote{It may be that exchange rate traders take time to adjust to the information that comes from order flow or it may be evidence of the \emph{conservatism heuristic} that suggests that people are slow to change their opinion to new information.}  

It is also possible to look at the distribution exchange rate returns after these extremes and to compare them to the distribution of the whole sample.  If speculation is informed, we expect to see a distribution of return that is largely symmetrical around zero and very similar to the distribution for the whole sample. The distribution of return is very similar but, but much broader than that of the whole distribution.  Conventionally, this would suggest that there is greater risk.  It may be that the increase in information adds to the level of uncertainty in the market. 
