There is little evidence that these self-reported speculators are driving prices away from fundamentals with their activity. Sixty percent of the S1 cases still show a significant abnormal return in the direction of the extreme 4 weeks after the extreme has been reached; only thirty percent of the cases show a reversal and in only one of those do ninety five percent of the re-sampled means remain above zero.  For S2 there is even less ambiguity, with ninety percent of the cases showing a continuation and forty percent of them being significant.  The evidence here with speculative positions is the same as that of speculative sentiment.  Prices move in the direction of speculative activity but speculative extremes do not provide information about the future. The price action of the event study is consistent with speculation being informed rather than uninformed.   

Figures \ref{fig:ES3} and \ref{fig:ES4} indicate that these results are not a function of the event window that has been chosen.  Looking at the 95 percentile confidence intervals (once again constructed by bootstrap re-sampling) indicates that in all the cases, there is a large amount of uncertainty about the future direction well after the extreme reading of speculative activity.  It does not appear that informed traders are constrained in the short-run from driving prices back to equilibrium.  It appears that the informed traders are driving prices to a new level. 

\section{Speculation and foreign exchange returns}
The nature speculative activity in financial markets is central to a number of contemporary policy questions.  Amongst these are the design and regulation of financial markets, the surge in commodity prices and the limits put on the activities of financial institutions. The debate about a tax on financial transactions, initiated by \citet{TobinTax} and now called the \emph{the Tobin tax}, has been intended to reduce speculation. This is based on the belief that speculation is uninformed, that it drive prices away from their fundamental value and as a consequence  increases the volatility of financial asset prices. The argument for a tax on financial transactions can be presented as a tax on an externality with the level of volatility of financial markets being the public cost.  

The increase in volatility that is evident when speculative activity is high seems to provide some support to this argument.  However, it is not clear that the direction of causality is from speculation to volatility.  An alternative view would suggest that an increase in information raises the amount of informed speculation and that this increase in information naturally increase the volatility of financial assets. If speculation is part of the process of price discovery, reducing its activity may reduce liquidity and hinder the process of price discovery.  In that case unanticipated costs may offset some of the benefits that are expected from the tax on speculation.      
  
Regulatory changes in the US government bond market give some hints at the way that reduce speculation can affect the smooth functioning of markets.\footnote{Increased capital requirements and the so-called \emph{Volcker Rule} that would prevent investment banks from trading on their own account have increased the cost of trading US government bonds and reduced the ability of some key players to participate in the market.}  Though bid-ask spreads have remained rather stable, the \emph{market-depth} and the \emph{price impact} of large trades has deteriorated in the last two years.  There have also been a number of occasions where very large price changes and an evaporation of liquidity have affected the market. 

The surge in commodities prices that was seen prior to the GFC was seen to be partially the consequence of increased speculation in commodities and the creation of exchange traded funds (ETF) focusing on commodities markets. Even if speculators are on both side of the market and not driving prices in one direction, they may still increase the amount of volatility, incurring costs for producers and consumers of underlying materials.   

This paper has sought to measure speculation and to use this measure to discover more about the relationship between speculation, information and asset prices.  
Whether measured as speculative sentiment or as the weight of speculator action, it is clear that extreme speculation does not provide information about future returns.  This means that speculation is more likely to be informed than uninformed.  If it were uninformed it would be much more likely that these extremes would be follow by reversals as informed market participants took advantage of the space created by this uninformed speculative activity. 



